     440            8 : function visitNode<T>(cbNode: (node: Node) => T, node: Node | undefined): T | undefined {
     441            8 :     return node && cbNode(node);

     443            8 : 
     444            8 : function visitNodes<T>(cbNode: (node: Node) => T, cbNodes: ((node: NodeArray<Node>) => T | undefined) | undefined, nodes: NodeArray<Node> | undefined): T | undefined {
     445            8 :     if (nodes) {
     446            8 :         if (cbNodes) {
     447            8 :             return cbNodes(nodes);
     448            8 :         }
     449            8 :         for (const node of nodes) {

     451            8 :             if (result) {

     454            8 :         }
     455            8 :     }
     456            8 : }

     465            8 : /** @internal */
     466            8 : export function isFileProbablyExternalModule(sourceFile: SourceFile) {
     467            8 :     // Try to use the first top-level import/export when available, then
     468            8 :     // fall back to looking for an 'import.meta' somewhere in the tree if necessary.
     469            8 :     return forEach(sourceFile.statements, isAnExternalModuleIndicatorNode) ||
     470            8 :         getImportMetaIfNecessary(sourceFile);
     471            8 : }
     472            8 : 
     473            8 : function isAnExternalModuleIndicatorNode(node: Node) {
     474            8 :     return canHaveModifiers(node) && hasModifierOfKind(node, SyntaxKind.ExportKeyword)
     475            8 :             || isImportEqualsDeclaration(node) && isExternalModuleReference(node.moduleReference)
     476            8 :             || isImportDeclaration(node)
     477            8 :             || isExportAssignment(node)
     478            8 :             || isExportDeclaration(node) ? node : undefined;
     479            8 : }
     480            8 : 
     481            8 : function getImportMetaIfNecessary(sourceFile: SourceFile) {
     482            8 :     return sourceFile.flags & NodeFlags.PossiblyContainsImportMeta ?
     483            8 :         walkTreeForImportMeta(sourceFile) :
     484            8 :         undefined;
     485            8 : }
     486            8 : 
     487            8 : function walkTreeForImportMeta(node: Node): Node | undefined {
     488            8 :     return isImportMeta(node) ? node : forEachChild(node, walkTreeForImportMeta);
     489            8 : }
     490            8 : 
     491            8 : /** Do not use hasModifier inside the parser; it relies on parent pointers. Use this instead. */
     492            8 : function hasModifierOfKind(node: HasModifiers, kind: SyntaxKind) {
     493            8 :     return some(node.modifiers, m => m.kind === kind);
     494            8 : }
     495            8 : 
     496            8 : function isImportMeta(node: Node): boolean {
     497            8 :     return isMetaProperty(node) && node.keywordToken === SyntaxKind.ImportKeyword && node.name.escapedText === "meta";

    1233            8 : /**
    1234            8 :  * Invokes a callback for each child of the given node. The 'cbNode' callback is invoked for all child nodes
    1235            8 :  * stored in properties. If a 'cbNodes' callback is specified, it is invoked for embedded arrays; otherwise,
    1236            8 :  * embedded arrays are flattened and the 'cbNode' callback is invoked for each element. If a callback returns
    1237            8 :  * a truthy value, iteration stops and that value is returned. Otherwise, undefined is returned.
    1238            8 :  *
    1239            8 :  * @param node a given node to visit its children
    1240            8 :  * @param cbNode a callback to be invoked for all child nodes
    1241            8 :  * @param cbNodes a callback to be invoked for embedded array
    1242            8 :  *
    1243            8 :  * @remarks `forEachChild` must visit the children of a node in the order
    1244            8 :  * that they appear in the source code. The language service depends on this property to locate nodes by position.
    1245            8 :  */
    1246            8 : export function forEachChild<T>(node: Node, cbNode: (node: Node) => T | undefined, cbNodes?: (nodes: NodeArray<Node>) => T | undefined): T | undefined {

    1248            8 :         return;
    1249            8 :     }
    1250            8 :     const fn = (forEachChildTable as Record<SyntaxKind, ForEachChildFunction<any>>)[node.kind];
    1251            8 :     return fn === undefined ? undefined : fn(node, cbNode, cbNodes);
    1252            8 : }
    1253            8 : 
    1254            8 : /**
    1255            8 :  * Invokes a callback for each child of the given node. The 'cbNode' callback is invoked for all child nodes
    1256            8 :  * stored in properties. If a 'cbNodes' callback is specified, it is invoked for embedded arrays; additionally,
    1257            8 :  * unlike `forEachChild`, embedded arrays are flattened and the 'cbNode' callback is invoked for each element.
    1258            8 :  *  If a callback returns a truthy value, iteration stops and that value is returned. Otherwise, undefined is returned.
    1259            8 :  *
    1260            8 :  * @param node a given node to visit its children
    1261            8 :  * @param cbNode a callback to be invoked for all child nodes
    1262            8 :  * @param cbNodes a callback to be invoked for embedded array
    1263            8 :  *
    1264            8 :  * @remarks Unlike `forEachChild`, `forEachChildRecursively` handles recursively invoking the traversal on each child node found,
    1265            8 :  * and while doing so, handles traversing the structure without relying on the callstack to encode the tree structure.
    1266            8 :  *
    1267            8 :  * @internal
    1268            8 :  */
    1269            8 : export function forEachChildRecursively<T>(rootNode: Node, cbNode: (node: Node, parent: Node) => T | "skip" | undefined, cbNodes?: (nodes: NodeArray<Node>, parent: Node) => T | "skip" | undefined): T | undefined {
    1270            8 :     const queue: (Node | NodeArray<Node>)[] = gatherPossibleChildren(rootNode);
    1271            8 :     const parents: Node[] = []; // tracks parent references for elements in queue
    1272            8 :     while (parents.length < queue.length) {
    1273            8 :         parents.push(rootNode);
    1274            8 :     }
    1275            8 :     while (queue.length !== 0) {
    1276            8 :         const current = queue.pop()!;
    1277            8 :         const parent = parents.pop()!;
    1278            8 :         if (isArray(current)) {
    1279            8 :             if (cbNodes) {
    1280            8 :                 const res = cbNodes(current, parent);
    1281            8 :                 if (res) {
    1282            8 :                     if (res === "skip") continue;
    1283            8 :                     return res;
    1284            8 :                 }
    1285            8 :             }
    1286            8 :             for (let i = current.length - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
    1287            8 :                 queue.push(current[i]);
    1288            8 :                 parents.push(parent);
    1289            8 :             }
    1290            8 :         }
    1291            8 :         else {
    1292            8 :             const res = cbNode(current, parent);
    1293            8 :             if (res) {
    1294            8 :                 if (res === "skip") continue;
    1295            8 :                 return res;
    1296            8 :             }
    1297            8 :             if (current.kind >= SyntaxKind.FirstNode) {
    1298            8 :                 // add children in reverse order to the queue, so popping gives the first child
    1299            8 :                 for (const child of gatherPossibleChildren(current)) {
    1300            8 :                     queue.push(child);
    1301            8 :                     parents.push(current);
    1302            8 :                 }
    1303            8 :             }
    1304            8 :         }
    1305            8 :     }
    1306            8 : }
    1307            8 : 
    1308            8 : function gatherPossibleChildren(node: Node) {
    1309            8 :     const children: (Node | NodeArray<Node>)[] = [];
    1310            8 :     forEachChild(node, addWorkItem, addWorkItem); // By using a stack above and `unshift` here, we emulate a depth-first preorder traversal
    1311            8 :     return children;
    1312            8 : 
    1313            8 :     function addWorkItem(n: Node | NodeArray<Node>) {
    1314            8 :         children.unshift(n);
    1315            8 :     }
    1316            8 : }

    1424            8 : // Implement the parser as a singleton module.  We do this for perf reasons because creating
    1425            8 : // parser instances can actually be expensive enough to impact us on projects with many source
    1426            8 : // files.
    1427            8 : namespace Parser {
    1428            8 :     // Why var? It avoids TDZ checks in the runtime which can be costly.
    1429            8 :     // See: https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/52924
    1430            8 :     /* eslint-disable no-var */
    1431            8 : 
    1432            8 :     // Share a single scanner across all calls to parse a source file.  This helps speed things
    1433            8 :     // up by avoiding the cost of creating/compiling scanners over and over again.
    1434            8 :     var scanner = createScanner(ScriptTarget.Latest, /*skipTrivia*/ true);
    1435            8 : 
    1436            8 :     var disallowInAndDecoratorContext = NodeFlags.DisallowInContext | NodeFlags.DecoratorContext;
    1437            8 : 
    1438            8 :     // capture constructors in 'initializeState' to avoid null checks
    1439            8 :     var NodeConstructor: new (kind: SyntaxKind, pos: number, end: number) => Node;
    1440            8 :     var TokenConstructor: new (kind: SyntaxKind, pos: number, end: number) => Node;
    1441            8 :     var IdentifierConstructor: new (kind: SyntaxKind.Identifier, pos: number, end: number) => Identifier;
    1442            8 :     var PrivateIdentifierConstructor: new (kind: SyntaxKind.PrivateIdentifier, pos: number, end: number) => PrivateIdentifier;
    1443            8 :     var SourceFileConstructor: new (kind: SyntaxKind.SourceFile, pos: number, end: number) => SourceFile;
    1444            8 : 
    1445            8 :     function countNode(node: Node) {
    1446     97224798 :         nodeCount++;
    1447     97224798 :         return node;
    1448     97224798 :     }
    1449            8 : 
    1450            8 :     // Rather than using `createBaseNodeFactory` here, we establish a `BaseNodeFactory` that closes over the
    1451            8 :     // constructors above, which are reset each time `initializeState` is called.
    1452            8 :     var baseNodeFactory: BaseNodeFactory = {
    1453            8 :         createBaseSourceFileNode: kind => countNode(new SourceFileConstructor(kind, /*pos*/ 0, /*end*/ 0)),
    1454            8 :         createBaseIdentifierNode: kind => countNode(new IdentifierConstructor(kind, /*pos*/ 0, /*end*/ 0)),
    1455            8 :         createBasePrivateIdentifierNode: kind => countNode(new PrivateIdentifierConstructor(kind, /*pos*/ 0, /*end*/ 0)),
    1456            8 :         createBaseTokenNode: kind => countNode(new TokenConstructor(kind, /*pos*/ 0, /*end*/ 0)),
    1457            8 :         createBaseNode: kind => countNode(new NodeConstructor(kind, /*pos*/ 0, /*end*/ 0)),

    1510            8 :     var notParenthesizedArrow: Set<number> | undefined;
    1511            8 : 
    1512            8 :     // Flags that dictate what parsing context we're in.  For example:
    1513            8 :     // Whether or not we are in strict parsing mode.  All that changes in strict parsing mode is
    1514            8 :     // that some tokens that would be considered identifiers may be considered keywords.
    1515            8 :     //
    1516            8 :     // When adding more parser context flags, consider which is the more common case that the
    1517            8 :     // flag will be in.  This should be the 'false' state for that flag.  The reason for this is
    1518            8 :     // that we don't store data in our nodes unless the value is in the *non-default* state.  So,
    1519            8 :     // for example, more often than code 'allows-in' (or doesn't 'disallow-in').  We opt for
    1520            8 :     // 'disallow-in' set to 'false'.  Otherwise, if we had 'allowsIn' set to 'true', then almost
    1521            8 :     // all nodes would need extra state on them to store this info.
    1522            8 :     //
    1523            8 :     // Note: 'allowIn' and 'allowYield' track 1:1 with the [in] and [yield] concepts in the ES6
    1524            8 :     // grammar specification.
    1525            8 :     //
    1526            8 :     // An important thing about these context concepts.  By default they are effectively inherited
    1527            8 :     // while parsing through every grammar production.  i.e. if you don't change them, then when
    1528            8 :     // you parse a sub-production, it will have the same context values as the parent production.
    1529            8 :     // This is great most of the time.  After all, consider all the 'expression' grammar productions
    1530            8 :     // and how nearly all of them pass along the 'in' and 'yield' context values:
    1531            8 :     //
    1532            8 :     // EqualityExpression[In, Yield] :
    1533            8 :     //      RelationalExpression[?In, ?Yield]
    1534            8 :     //      EqualityExpression[?In, ?Yield] == RelationalExpression[?In, ?Yield]
    1535            8 :     //      EqualityExpression[?In, ?Yield] != RelationalExpression[?In, ?Yield]
    1536            8 :     //      EqualityExpression[?In, ?Yield] === RelationalExpression[?In, ?Yield]
    1537            8 :     //      EqualityExpression[?In, ?Yield] !== RelationalExpression[?In, ?Yield]
    1538            8 :     //
    1539            8 :     // Where you have to be careful is then understanding what the points are in the grammar
    1540            8 :     // where the values are *not* passed along.  For example:
    1541            8 :     //
    1542            8 :     // SingleNameBinding[Yield,GeneratorParameter]
    1543            8 :     //      [+GeneratorParameter]BindingIdentifier[Yield] Initializer[In]opt
    1544            8 :     //      [~GeneratorParameter]BindingIdentifier[?Yield]Initializer[In, ?Yield]opt
    1545            8 :     //
    1546            8 :     // Here this is saying that if the GeneratorParameter context flag is set, that we should
    1547            8 :     // explicitly set the 'yield' context flag to false before calling into the BindingIdentifier
    1548            8 :     // and we should explicitly unset the 'yield' context flag before calling into the Initializer.
    1549            8 :     // production.  Conversely, if the GeneratorParameter context flag is not set, then we
    1550            8 :     // should leave the 'yield' context flag alone.
    1551            8 :     //
    1552            8 :     // Getting this all correct is tricky and requires careful reading of the grammar to
    1553            8 :     // understand when these values should be changed versus when they should be inherited.
    1554            8 :     //
    1555            8 :     // Note: it should not be necessary to save/restore these flags during speculative/lookahead
    1556            8 :     // parsing.  These context flags are naturally stored and restored through normal recursive
    1557            8 :     // descent parsing and unwinding.
    1558            8 :     var contextFlags: NodeFlags;
    1559            8 : 
    1560            8 :     // Indicates whether we are currently parsing top-level statements.
    1561            8 :     var topLevel = true;
    1562            8 : 
    1563            8 :     // Whether or not we've had a parse error since creating the last AST node.  If we have
    1564            8 :     // encountered an error, it will be stored on the next AST node we create.  Parse errors
    1565            8 :     // can be broken down into three categories:
    1566            8 :     //
    1567            8 :     // 1) An error that occurred during scanning.  For example, an unterminated literal, or a
    1568            8 :     //    character that was completely not understood.
    1569            8 :     //
    1570            8 :     // 2) A token was expected, but was not present.  This type of error is commonly produced
    1571            8 :     //    by the 'parseExpected' function.
    1572            8 :     //
    1573            8 :     // 3) A token was present that no parsing function was able to consume.  This type of error
    1574            8 :     //    only occurs in the 'abortParsingListOrMoveToNextToken' function when the parser
    1575            8 :     //    decides to skip the token.
    1576            8 :     //
    1577            8 :     // In all of these cases, we want to mark the next node as having had an error before it.
    1578            8 :     // With this mark, we can know in incremental settings if this node can be reused, or if
    1579            8 :     // we have to reparse it.  If we don't keep this information around, we may just reuse the
    1580            8 :     // node.  in that event we would then not produce the same errors as we did before, causing
    1581            8 :     // significant confusion problems.
    1582            8 :     //
    1583            8 :     // Note: it is necessary that this value be saved/restored during speculative/lookahead
    1584            8 :     // parsing.  During lookahead parsing, we will often create a node.  That node will have
    1585            8 :     // this value attached, and then this value will be set back to 'false'.  If we decide to
    1586            8 :     // rewind, we must get back to the same value we had prior to the lookahead.
    1587            8 :     //
    1588            8 :     // Note: any errors at the end of the file that do not precede a regular node, should get
    1589            8 :     // attached to the EOF token.
    1590            8 :     var parseErrorBeforeNextFinishedNode = false;
    1591            8 :     /* eslint-enable no-var */

    2246            8 :     function speculationHelper<T>(callback: () => T, speculationKind: SpeculationKind): T {
    2247     43632055 :         // Keep track of the state we'll need to rollback to if lookahead fails (or if the
    2248     43632055 :         // caller asked us to always reset our state).
    2249     43632055 :         const saveToken = currentToken;
    2250     43632055 :         const saveParseDiagnosticsLength = parseDiagnostics.length;
    2251     43632055 :         const saveParseErrorBeforeNextFinishedNode = parseErrorBeforeNextFinishedNode;
    2252     43632055 : 
    2253     43632055 :         // Note: it is not actually necessary to save/restore the context flags here.  That's
    2254     43632055 :         // because the saving/restoring of these flags happens naturally through the recursive
    2255     43632055 :         // descent nature of our parser.  However, we still store this here just so we can
    2256     43632055 :         // assert that invariant holds.
    2257     43632055 :         const saveContextFlags = contextFlags;
    2258     43632055 : 
    2259     43632055 :         // If we're only looking ahead, then tell the scanner to only lookahead as well.
    2260     43632055 :         // Otherwise, if we're actually speculatively parsing, then tell the scanner to do the
    2261     43632055 :         // same.
    2262     43632055 :         const result = speculationKind !== SpeculationKind.TryParse
    2263     22871793 :             ? scanner.lookAhead(callback)
    2264     20760262 :             : scanner.tryScan(callback);
    2265     43632055 : 
    2266     43632055 :         Debug.assert(saveContextFlags === contextFlags);
    2267     43632055 : 
    2268     43632055 :         // If our callback returned something 'falsy' or we're just looking ahead,
    2269     43632055 :         // then unconditionally restore us to where we were.
    2270     43632055 :         if (!result || speculationKind !== SpeculationKind.TryParse) {
    2271     31445496 :             currentToken = saveToken;
    2272     31445496 :             if (speculationKind !== SpeculationKind.Reparse) {
    2273     31445439 :                 parseDiagnostics.length = saveParseDiagnosticsLength;
    2274     31445439 :             }
    2275     31445496 :             parseErrorBeforeNextFinishedNode = saveParseErrorBeforeNextFinishedNode;
    2276     31445496 :         }
    2277     43632055 : 
    2278     43632055 :         return result;
    2279     43632055 :     }
    2280            8 :

    3362          682 : 
    3363          682 :         // Very subtle incremental parsing bug.  Consider the following code:
    3364          682 :         //
    3365          682 :         //      let v = new List < A, B
    3366          682 :         //

    3595            8 :     function parseRightSideOfDot(allowIdentifierNames: boolean, allowPrivateIdentifiers: boolean, allowUnicodeEscapeSequenceInIdentifierName: boolean): Identifier | PrivateIdentifier {
    3596       221165 :         // Technically a keyword is valid here as all identifiers and keywords are identifier names.
    3597       221165 :         // However, often we'll encounter this in error situations when the identifier or keyword
    3598       221165 :         // is actually starting another valid construct.
    3599       221165 :         //
    3600       221165 :         // So, we check for the following specific case:
    3601       221165 :         //
    3602       221165 :         //      name.
    3603       221165 :         //      identifierOrKeyword identifierNameOrKeyword
    3604       221165 :         //
    3605       221165 :         // Note: the newlines are important here.  For example, if that above code
    3606       221165 :         // were rewritten into:
    3607       221165 :         //
    3608       221165 :         //      name.identifierOrKeyword
    3609       221165 :         //      identifierNameOrKeyword
    3610       221165 :         //
    3611       221165 :         // Then we would consider it valid.  That's because ASI would take effect and
    3612       221165 :         // the code would be implicitly: "name.identifierOrKeyword; identifierNameOrKeyword".

    5940            8 :     function parseMemberExpressionOrHigher(): MemberExpression {
    5941      1796497 :         // Note: to make our lives simpler, we decompose the NewExpression productions and
    5942      1796497 :         // place ObjectCreationExpression and FunctionExpression into PrimaryExpression.
    5943      1796497 :         // like so:
    5944      1796497 :         //
    5945      1796497 :         //   PrimaryExpression : See 11.1
    5946      1796497 :         //      this
    5947      1796497 :         //      Identifier
    5948      1796497 :         //      Literal
    5949      1796497 :         //      ArrayLiteral
    5950      1796497 :         //      ObjectLiteral
    5951      1796497 :         //      (Expression)
    5952      1796497 :         //      FunctionExpression
    5953      1796497 :         //      new MemberExpression Arguments?
    5954      1796497 :         //
    5955      1796497 :         //   MemberExpression : See 11.2
    5956      1796497 :         //      PrimaryExpression
    5957      1796497 :         //      MemberExpression[Expression]
    5958      1796497 :         //      MemberExpression.IdentifierName
    5959      1796497 :         //
    5960      1796497 :         //   CallExpression : See 11.2
    5961      1796497 :         //      MemberExpression
    5962      1796497 :         //      CallExpression Arguments
    5963      1796497 :         //      CallExpression[Expression]
    5964      1796497 :         //      CallExpression.IdentifierName
    5965      1796497 :         //
    5966      1796497 :         // Technically this is ambiguous.  i.e. CallExpression defines:
    5967      1796497 :         //
    5968      1796497 :         //   CallExpression:
    5969      1796497 :         //      CallExpression Arguments
    5970      1796497 :         //
    5971      1796497 :         // If you see: "new Foo()"

    5973      1796497 :         // Then that could be treated as a single ObjectCreationExpression, or it could be
    5974      1796497 :         // treated as the invocation of "new Foo".  We disambiguate that in code (to match
    5975      1796497 :         // the original grammar) by making sure that if we see an ObjectCreationExpression
    5976      1796497 :         // we always consume arguments if they are there. So we treat "new Foo()" as an
    5977      1796497 :         // object creation only, and not at all as an invocation.  Another way to think

    5979      1796497 :         // it is there as part of the *associated* object creation node.  Any additional
    5980      1796497 :         // argument lists we see, will become invocation expressions.
    5981      1796497 :         //
    5982      1796497 :         // Because there are no other places in the grammar now that refer to FunctionExpression

    5984      1796497 :         // production.

    5988      1796497 :         const pos = getNodePos();
    5989      1796497 :         const expression = parsePrimaryExpression();
    5990      1796497 :         return parseMemberExpressionRest(pos, expression, /*allowOptionalChain*/ true);
    5991      1796497 :     }

    9931         5370 :         // If we added or removed characters during the edit, then we need to go and adjust all
    9932         5370 :         // the nodes after the edit.  Those nodes may move forward (if we inserted chars) or they
    9933         5370 :         // may move backward (if we deleted chars).

    9935         5370 :         // Doing this helps us out in two ways.  First, it means that any nodes/tokens we want
    9936         5370 :         // to reuse are already at the appropriate position in the new text.  That way when we
    9937         5370 :         // reuse them, we don't have to figure out if they need to be adjusted.  Second, it makes
    9938         5370 :         // it very easy to determine if we can reuse a node.  If the node's position is at where
    9939         5370 :         // we are in the text, then we can reuse it.  Otherwise we can't.  If the node's position

   10082            8 :     function adjustIntersectingElement(element: Node | NodeArray<Node>, changeStart: number, changeRangeOldEnd: number, changeRangeNewEnd: number, delta: number) {
   10083        54043 :         Debug.assert(element.end >= changeStart, "Adjusting an element that was entirely before the change range");
   10084        54043 :         Debug.assert(element.pos <= changeRangeOldEnd, "Adjusting an element that was entirely after the change range");
   10085        54043 :         Debug.assert(element.pos <= element.end);
   10086        54043 : 
   10087        54043 :         // We have an element that intersects the change range in some way.  It may have its
   10088        54043 :         // start, or its end (or both) in the changed range.  We want to adjust any part
   10089        54043 :         // that intersects such that the final tree is in a consistent state.  i.e. all
   10090        54043 :         // children have spans within the span of their parent, and all siblings are ordered
   10091        54043 :         // properly.
   10092        54043 : 
   10093        54043 :         // We may need to update both the 'pos' and the 'end' of the element.
   10094        54043 : 
   10095        54043 :         // If the 'pos' is before the start of the change, then we don't need to touch it.
   10096        54043 :         // If it isn't, then the 'pos' must be inside the change.  How we update it will
   10097        54043 :         // depend if delta is positive or negative. If delta is positive then we have
   10098        54043 :         // something like:
   10099        54043 :         //
   10100        54043 :         //  -------------------AAA-----------------
   10101        54043 :         //  -------------------BBBCCCCCCC-----------------
   10102        54043 :         //
   10103        54043 :         // In this case, we consider any node that started in the change range to still be
   10104        54043 :         // starting at the same position.
   10105        54043 :         //
   10106        54043 :         // however, if the delta is negative, then we instead have something like this:
   10107        54043 :         //
   10108        54043 :         //  -------------------XXXYYYYYYY-----------------
   10109        54043 :         //  -------------------ZZZ-----------------
   10110        54043 :         //
   10111        54043 :         // In this case, any element that started in the 'X' range will keep its position.
   10112        54043 :         // However any element that started after that will have their pos adjusted to be
   10113        54043 :         // at the end of the new range.  i.e. any node that started in the 'Y' range will
   10114        54043 :         // be adjusted to have their start at the end of the 'Z' range.
   10115        54043 :         //
   10116        54043 :         // The element will keep its position if possible.  Or Move backward to the new-end
   10117        54043 :         // if it's in the 'Y' range.
   10118        54043 :         const pos = Math.min(element.pos, changeRangeNewEnd);
   10119        54043 : 
   10120        54043 :         // If the 'end' is after the change range, then we always adjust it by the delta
   10121        54043 :         // amount.  However, if the end is in the change range, then how we adjust it
   10122        54043 :         // will depend on if delta is positive or negative.  If delta is positive then we
   10123        54043 :         // have something like:
   10124        54043 :         //
   10125        54043 :         //  -------------------AAA-----------------
   10126        54043 :         //  -------------------BBBCCCCCCC-----------------
   10127        54043 :         //
   10128        54043 :         // In this case, we consider any node that ended inside the change range to keep its
   10129        54043 :         // end position.
   10130        54043 :         //
   10131        54043 :         // however, if the delta is negative, then we instead have something like this:
   10132        54043 :         //
   10133        54043 :         //  -------------------XXXYYYYYYY-----------------
   10134        54043 :         //  -------------------ZZZ-----------------
   10135        54043 :         //
   10136        54043 :         // In this case, any element that ended in the 'X' range will keep its position.
   10137        54043 :         // However any element that ended after that will have their pos adjusted to be
   10138        54043 :         // at the end of the new range.  i.e. any node that ended in the 'Y' range will
   10139        54043 :         // be adjusted to have their end at the end of the 'Z' range.
   10140        54043 :         const end = element.end >= changeRangeOldEnd ?
   10141        35801 :             // Element ends after the change range.  Always adjust the end pos.
   10142        35801 :             element.end + delta :
   10143        18242 :             // Element ends in the change range.  The element will keep its position if
   10144        18242 :             // possible. Or Move backward to the new-end if it's in the 'Y' range.
   10145        18242 :             Math.min(element.end, changeRangeNewEnd);
   10146        54043 : 
   10147        54043 :         Debug.assert(pos <= end);
   10148        54043 :         if ((element as any).parent) {
   10149        35858 :             const parent = (element as any).parent as Node;
   10150        35858 :             Debug.assertGreaterThanOrEqual(pos, parent.pos);
   10151        35858 :             Debug.assertLessThanOrEqual(end, parent.end);
   10152        35858 :         }
   10153        54043 : 
   10154        54043 :         setTextRangePosEnd(element, pos, end);
   10155        54043 :     }

   10249            8 :     function extendToAffectedRange(sourceFile: SourceFile, changeRange: TextChangeRange): TextChangeRange {
   10250         5370 :         // Consider the following code:
   10251         5370 :         //      void foo() { /; }
   10252         5370 :         //
   10253         5370 :         // If the text changes with an insertion of / just before the semicolon then we end up with:
   10254         5370 :         //      void foo() { //; }
   10255         5370 :         //
   10256         5370 :         // If we were to just use the changeRange a is, then we would not rescan the { token
   10257         5370 :         // (as it does not intersect the actual original change range).  Because an edit may
   10258         5370 :         // change the token touching it, we actually need to look back *at least* one token so
   10259         5370 :         // that the prior token sees that change.
   10260         5370 :         const maxLookahead = 1;
   10261         5370 :

   10390            8 :     export function createSyntaxCursor(sourceFile: SourceFile): SyntaxCursor {
   10391         5403 :         let currentArray: NodeArray<Node> = sourceFile.statements;
   10392         5403 :         let currentArrayIndex = 0;
   10393         5403 : 
   10394         5403 :         Debug.assert(currentArrayIndex < currentArray.length);

   10396         5403 :         let lastQueriedPosition = InvalidPosition.Value;
   10397         5403 : 
   10398         5403 :         return {
   10399         5403 :             currentNode(position: number) {
   10400        57256 :                 // Only compute the current node if the position is different than the last time
   10401        57256 :                 // we were asked.  The parser commonly asks for the node at the same position
   10402        57256 :                 // twice.  Once to know if can read an appropriate list element at a certain point,
   10403        57256 :                 // and then to actually read and consume the node.

   10405        28990 :                     // Much of the time the parser will need the very next node in the array that
   10406        28990 :                     // we just returned a node from.So just simply check for that case and move
   10407        28990 :                     // forward in the array instead of searching for the node again.
   10408        28990 :                     if (current && current.end === position && currentArrayIndex < (currentArray.length - 1)) {
   10409        12548 :                         currentArrayIndex++;
   10410        12548 :                         current = currentArray[currentArrayIndex];
   10411        12548 :                     }
   10412        28990 : 
   10413        28990 :                     // If we don't have a node, or the node we have isn't in the right position,
   10414        28990 :                     // then try to find a viable node at the position requested.
   10415        28990 :                     if (!current || current.pos !== position) {

   10417        11743 :                     }
   10418        28990 :                 }

   10420        57256 :                 // Cache this query so that we don't do any extra work if the parser calls back
   10421        57256 :                 // into us.  Note: this is very common as the parser will make pairs of calls like
   10422        57256 :                 // 'isListElement -> parseListElement'.  If we were unable to find a node when

   10433         5403 :         // Finds the highest element in the tree we can find that starts at the provided position.
